    "body": "### Problem\n\nSaving a session that contains a terminal, and then loading that session, gives an error in the loaded buffer that the shell path is wrong. For example in my case where my shell path is set in a Lua file via `vim.opt.shell = '\"C:\\\\Program Files\\\\PowerShell\\\\7\\\\pwsh.exe\" -NoLogo'`, I get this error in the buffer, \n\n```\nC:/Program: The term 'C:/Program' is not recognized as a n\name of a cmdlet, function, script file, or executable prog\nram.\nCheck the spelling of the name, or if a path was included,\n verify that the path is correct and try again.\n\n[Process exited 1]\n```\nIn the session file created, you can see the path has a slash that is probably getting read as another folder. The path at the start is where the shell variable gets set in my config.\n\n`term://~/AppData/Local/nvim/lua//14836:C:/Program\\ Files/PowerShell/7/pwsh.exe`\n\nThis issue was mentioned [in the forum about 2.5 years ago](https://neovim.discourse.group/t/mksession-doesnt-properly-bring-back-terminal-buffers-powershell-windows/3371) with no response unfortunately.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Set the shell path to somewhere with spaces\n2. Open nvim and open a terminal buffer\n3. Create a session manually via `mksession test.vim`. That'll create a session called test.vim in the current directory\n4. Exit nvim\n5. Run `nvim -S test.vim`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nFor the shell to be loaded in the terminal buffer after loading a session.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.10.4 Build type: Release LuaJIT 2.1.1713484068\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nGives a `CreateProcess failed` error when setting shell to be the pwsh path. Unsure if I'm setting it up correctly\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWin 11\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nPowershell 7\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nI think Windows doesn't have this?\n\n### Installation\n\nwinget",
